## Environments & Deployment

We use [GitHub Flow](https://docs.github.com/en/get-started/using-github/github-flow): one long-lived branch (`main`), short-lived branches per issue, a Vercel preview deployment (with its own Neon database branch) per PR, and production deploys on merge to `main`. **There is no `staging` branch.** If you need a shared environment for QA or stakeholder review, use a Vercel preview alias â€” never a long-lived branch (see Hard Rule #3).

| Environment | Branch / Source | URL | Database |
|---|---|---|---|
| Development | Local checkout | `http://localhost:3000` | Neon dev branch |
| Preview (per PR) | Open PR against `main` | `<project>-<pr>.vercel.app` | Neon preview branch (auto-created per PR) |
| Production | `main` | `TODO: your-domain.com` | Neon `main` branch |

**Deploy flow:** issue â†’ branch from `main` (`<type>/<N>-<slug>`) â†’ PR to `main` â†’ CI + Vercel preview â†’ smoke-test the preview â†’ squash-merge â†’ production auto-deploys

**Vercel region:** `TODO: your-region` (set in `vercel.json`)

> **Merge UI gotcha â€” every GitHub merge button rewrites commit SHAs.** Squash merge creates one new commit on the target branch; rebase merge creates new commits with new committer signatures; merge-commit creates a merge node. **None of them are true fast-forwards.** Only `git push --ff-only` from CLI is. The single-branch model is what makes this safe â€” with one long-lived branch you don't care about SHA rewriting because there's no second branch to keep in sync. Reintroduce a second long-lived branch and you immediately re-create the divergence problem regardless of which merge button you click.

## Hard Rules

1. **Australian spelling throughout** â€” favour, colour, organisation, behaviour, licence (noun). Applies to all prose, comments, and string literals.

2. **Issue before branch** â€” every change starts as a GitHub issue, even one-line fixes. Branch names must encode the issue number: `<type>/<issue-number>-<slug>` where `<type>` is one of `feat`, `fix`, `chore`, `docs`. Example: `feat/42-user-profile`. The commit footer references the issue (`Refs: #42`) and the PR body uses `Closes #42`. No exceptions â€” including for hotfixes.

3. **One long-lived branch (`main`)** â€” use GitHub Flow. Never create a `staging`, `develop`, or `release/*` long-lived branch. If you need a shared environment for QA, use a Vercel preview alias. Long-lived secondary branches drift on every merge because **every** GitHub merge button rewrites SHAs in some form, and the only true fast-forward is `git push --ff-only` from CLI.

4. **Any merge between two long-lived branches diverges them.** Squash merge creates a new commit on the target branch with a new SHA. Rebase merge creates new commits with new committer signatures. Merge-commit creates a merge node and a new commit object. **None of these are true fast-forwards** â€” only `git push --ff-only` from CLI is. Therefore: do not run two long-lived branches at all. With a single long-lived branch (`main`) this rule is automatic â€” squash merge is fine because there is no second branch to keep in sync. Use squash merge as the default merge button (it produces the cleanest linear history) but remember that the *real* protection is the single-branch model, not the merge button choice.

5. **Plan before code** â€” always use the plan â†’ approve â†’ execute pattern. Never write code without an approved plan. Never skip the plan step.

   **Plan-mode hygiene:** every plan must (a) confirm "missing/needs verification" claims against the actual files via a `Read`, not from memory; (b) reference critical files by full repo-relative path so the implementation phase doesn't re-grep; (c) reference the issue templates and label vocabulary (`type:*`/`scope:*`) so issues can be filed without re-discovery; (d) include a "What's already in place (excluded from this plan)" section near the top â€” see `docs/templates/technical-spec.md`. See `docs/guides/agentic-workflow.md` Phase 5 for the worked patterns.

6. **Spec-driven development** â€” every feature starts as a spec document in `docs/specs/` before any code is written. Specs are committed to the repo.

7. **No business logic in chores** â€” a `chore:` PR must contain only the chore. If you're upgrading a dependency and notice an unrelated bug in the file you're touching, **file a separate issue and address it in its own PR**. Do not bundle bug fixes, refactors, or feature work into a chore commit. Reviewers should be able to skim a chore PR in 30 seconds and merge with confidence; unrelated changes destroy that property and make bisection painful.

   *Concrete example:* You're bumping a logging library version. The diff is a one-line `package.json` change and a regenerated lockfile. While testing the upgrade you notice that one of the call sites swallows a thrown error in a `try { ... } catch {}` block. Do **not** add `catch (err) { logger.error(err) }` to the same PR â€” file a `fix:` issue, ship the chore, then fix the bug as PR #2. The chore stays auditable and the fix gets a proper test.

8. **Verify file existence before recommending it from memory** â€” a recall that names a specific file path, function, flag, or symbol is a claim about a *past* state of the repo. Before proposing to use, backport, or refer to it, **read the file** (or grep for the symbol) and confirm it still exists with the shape you remember. Renames, deletes, and refactors invalidate memories silently and the only safe thing to do is re-verify at the moment of recommendation.

   *Concrete example:* You remember a `lib/cache.ts` helper called `dedupeByKey(items, fn)` from earlier in the project and you're about to recommend it. **Before** suggesting it: read `src/lib/cache.ts`, confirm `dedupeByKey` is still exported, and confirm its signature still matches the call site you have in mind. If the file moved to `src/lib/utils/dedupe.ts` or the function was renamed to `uniqueBy`, the recommendation is wrong even though the *idea* was right. Recommending stale memories costs more cycles than the recall saves.

9. **Expand-migrate-contract for schema changes** â€” never ship a destructive schema change (column drop, rename, type change, NOT NULL on existing data) in a single PR. Split it across deploys:

   1. **Expand:** add the new column/table alongside the old one. Deploy. Both old and new code paths work.
   2. **Migrate:** backfill data into the new shape. Switch reads and writes to the new column. Deploy.
   3. **Contract:** drop the old column once nothing references it. Deploy.

   *Why:* Vercel rolling deploys run old and new code concurrently for ~30 seconds during a release. A single-PR rename means the old containers query a column that no longer exists and start serving 500s mid-deploy.

   *Concrete example â€” renaming `users.email` to `users.email_address`:*
   - **PR 1 (expand):** add `email_address` column nullable, write to both `email` and `email_address`, read from `email`.
   - **PR 2 (migrate):** backfill `email_address` from `email`, switch reads to `email_address`, drop the dual-write.
   - **PR 3 (contract):** drop the `email` column.

   For pure additive changes (new column, new table, new index) you can ship all three steps in one PR â€” the rule only kicks in when something is being removed, renamed, or made stricter.

   **Pre-launch corollary:** while you have no real users and the dev DB is fully reseedable, drop the ceremony â€” reseed freely, rename columns in one PR, do whatever shape changes the design needs. The rule kicks in the moment you have users you can't safely lose. Don't carry pre-launch complexity into post-launch ops, and don't carry post-launch ceremony back into pre-launch iteration.

10. **No `any` types** â€” TypeScript strict mode is non-negotiable. Use proper generics, union types, or `unknown` with type guards. ESLint enforces `no-explicit-any`.

11. **No `console.log`** â€” use the structured logger at `src/lib/logger.ts`. ESLint enforces `no-console`. The logger produces JSON with timestamps and levels.

12. **All API responses use the envelope** â€” `{ success: true, data: T }` or `{ success: false, error: { message, code } }`. Use `ok()`, `created()`, `noContent()`, `handleError()` from `src/lib/api-response.ts`.

13. **Auth via `getAuth()` only** â€” never call `auth()` directly in route handlers. Always use `getAuth()` from `src/lib/auth/get-auth.ts` which handles both Clerk sessions and mobile JWT.

14. **Validate all inputs with Zod** â€” every API endpoint validates request body and query params with Zod schemas. Schemas live in `src/lib/validations/`. Never trust user input.

15. **Rate limit all endpoints** â€” use `checkRateLimit()` from `src/lib/rate-limit.ts`. Public endpoints get `publicRateLimiter`, write operations get `writeRateLimiter`, authenticated requests get `rateLimiter`.

16. **Soft delete, never hard delete** â€” set `status = 'deleted'`, never `DELETE FROM`. All queries should filter out deleted records.

## Labels

Apply at least one `type:*` and one `scope:*` label to every issue and PR. The label taxonomy is created on a fresh repo by `claude-config/scripts/setup-labels.sh`.

| Group | Labels | When to use |
|---|---|---|
| `type:*` | `type:feature`, `type:fix`, `type:chore`, `type:docs` | What kind of change is this? |
| `scope:*` | `scope:api`, `scope:dashboard`, `scope:mobile`, `scope:schema`, `scope:auth`, `scope:workflow` | Which area of the codebase? |
| `vertical:*` | TODO: project-specific (e.g. `vertical:billing`, `vertical:onboarding`) | Optional â€” only if your product has clearly distinct verticals |
| Status | `needs-triage`, `blocked`, `urgent` | Triage state â€” applied as needed |

The `<type>` segment of the branch name (`feat/`, `fix/`, `chore/`, `docs/`) must match the `type:*` label on the issue.

## Reusable Infrastructure

These modules ship in `src/lib/*` â€” **reach for them before writing new helpers**. If you find yourself rolling a logger, an env-checker, a Drizzle wrapper, or an auth resolver, stop and check this list first.

| Module | Path | Purpose |
|---|---|---|
| **Structured logger** | `src/lib/logger.ts` | JSON logger with timestamps/levels. Replaces `console.log` (which is lint-banned). |
| **Rate limit** | `src/lib/rate-limit.ts` | Upstash sliding-window limiters: `publicRateLimiter`, `writeRateLimiter`, `rateLimiter`, `loginRateLimiter` (5 req / 15 min). Use `checkRateLimit()` from every endpoint. |
| **Request context** | `src/lib/request-context.ts` | AsyncLocalStorage-backed `getRequestContext()` that returns `{ ip, userAgent, requestId }` from anywhere in the call stack. |
| **Mobile JWT** | `src/lib/mobile-jwt.ts` | `signMobileJwt()` / `verifyMobileJwt()` (jose) for the mobile auth path. |
| **API response envelope** | `src/lib/api-response.ts` | `ok()`, `created()`, `noContent()`, `handleError()`, `ApiError`. All API routes go through these â€” **do not** return raw `NextResponse.json()`. |
| **Dual-mode auth** | `src/lib/auth/get-auth.ts` | `getAuth()` resolves both Clerk sessions (web) and mobile JWT (Authorization: Bearer) into a single internal user. **Always use this â€” never call Clerk's `auth()` directly in route handlers.** |
| **Clerk user sync** | `src/lib/auth/resolve-clerk-user.ts` | Webhook handler that upserts the local `users` row when Clerk fires `user.created/updated/deleted`. |
| **Auth routing** | `src/lib/auth-routing.ts` | Public/protected route lists, role-based access helpers. |
| **Server actions** | `src/lib/actions/index.ts` | `action()` and `authAction()` wrappers â€” auth + error handling for Server Actions. |
| **Database** | `src/lib/db/index.ts`, `src/lib/db/schema.ts` | Neon HTTP client + Drizzle schema. |
| **Validations** | `src/lib/validations/index.ts` | Shared Zod schemas (`parsePagination`, UUID, etc.). |
| **Background jobs** | `src/lib/jobs/client.ts` | Inngest client. Opt-in â€” gracefully skips if `INNGEST_*` env vars are unset. |
| **Storage** | `src/lib/storage/index.ts` | Cloudflare R2 helpers. Opt-in. |
| **Email** | `src/lib/email/send.ts` | Resend wrapper. Opt-in. |
| **Stripe** | `src/lib/stripe/client.ts` | Stripe client. Opt-in. |
| **Misc** | `src/lib/utils.ts` | `cn()` Tailwind classname helper (clsx + tailwind-merge). |

> **Why this list exists:** the most expensive class of mistake on a long-running project is reinventing infrastructure that already exists. Before opening a new file in `src/lib/`, scan this table. If a module seems close-but-not-quite, extend it instead of duplicating it.

